⚖ DOCTRINE-024 — THE TIMEOUT MESSAGE IS PARAMOUNT
Every SESSION_TIMEOUT event MUST include the disclaimer in its raw_payload stating the closure is an evidentiary container boundary and does not imply gate-out, work completion, physical exit, or fault.

Every UI element that displays a TIMED_OUT session must include visible language to this effect. Never use phrases like ‘session expired,’ ‘detention ended,’ ‘driver departed,’ or ‘timed out successfully.’ The correct phrasing is:

• Dashboard badge: ‘TIMED OUT — Container closed, not exit’
• Session detail header: ‘This session reached the maximum duration and was automatically closed. This closure does not indicate the driver or vehicle left the facility.’
• Evidence packet: as specified in Section 6 below.


SECTION 5 — MERGE PREVENTION & AUDIT
🚫 DOCTRINE-025 — THESE OPERATIONS ARE FORBIDDEN
No SQL query, view, materialized view, Edge Function, API endpoint, export, or UI component may perform ANY of these operations:

• Combine events from multiple session_ids into a single logical ‘session’ representation.
• Accept a request payload containing a session_ids array for ‘merge,’ ‘consolidate,’ or ‘unify.’
• Present two distinct sessions to a user or external system as a single continuous timeline with shared identity.
• Produce an evidence packet whose session_id field contains more than one value.
• Insert events with multiple session_id references (the session_id column is NOT NULL and scalar — structurally impossible).

Two sessions MAY be displayed ADJACENTLY in a UI or report for the SAME driver/facility, provided they have distinct Session IDs, distinct hash chains, and distinct evidence packets, with clear visual separation and labels.

5.1 — Database-Level Enforcement
-- Trigger that blocks any INSERT into session_events attempting to
-- reference multiple session_ids (impossible by column type, but we
-- add a defensive check for any column-level manipulation attempts)

-- The session_events table already enforces session_id as a scalar UUID
-- via FOREIGN KEY REFERENCES sessions(id). This is structurally sufficient.

-- Additional audit trigger: log any UPDATE attempt on session_events,session_id
CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION log_session_id_tampering_attempt()
  RETURNS TRIGGER AS $$
BEGIN
  IF OLD.session_id IS DISTINCT FROM NEW.session_id THEN
    -- This should be impossible because UPDATE is revoked, but log it
    -- defensively in case of privilege escalation
    INSERT INTO session_merge_audit_log (
      attempted_by, attempt_source, session_ids,
      operation, rejected, rejection_reason
    ) VALUES (
      (SELECT auth.uid()), 'sql_update',
      ARRAY[OLD.session_id, NEW.session_id], 'session_id_change',
      true, 'Session ID reassignment is forbidden (DOCTRINE-025)'
    );
    RAISE EXCEPTION
      'DOCTRINE-025 VIOLATION: Session ID reassignment forbidden';
  END IF;
  RETURN NEW;
END;
$$ LANGUAGE plpgsql SECURITY DEFINER;

CREATE TRIGGER trg_block_session_id_change
  BEFORE UPDATE ON session_events
  FOR EACH ROW
  EXECUTE FUNCTION log_session_id_tampering_attempt();
5.2 — Application-Level Enforcement
Every Edge Function that accepts a session_code or session_id as input must validate that it is a single scalar value. Any request payload containing a session_ids array (plural) must be rejected with HTTP 400 and logged to session_merge_audit_log.
5.3 — Export-Level Enforcement
The evidence packet generator (Part #1, extended in #2 and #3) must enforce: one packet = one session. If a user requests an ‘evidence packet’ for multiple sessions, the system must produce MULTIPLE separate packets (zipped together for convenience) — never a single combined packet. Each packet must have its own packet_hash and session_hash.

