⚠ FINAL DOCTRINE GATE — PART #4
Before presenting any code, run this mental checklist:
(1) Does ANY UI element, log message, or data structure conflate SESSION_TIMEOUT with CHECK_OUT? If yes → SEVERE VIOLATION of DOCTRINE-024. FIX IMMEDIATELY.
(2) Can a session close by any mechanism other than CHECK_OUT, MANUAL_CLOSE, SESSION_TIMEOUT, or FORCED_CLOSE_ON_OVERLAP? If yes → FIX. (DOCTRINE-023)
(3) Can a session re-open after closure (OPEN → CLOSED/TIMED_OUT → OPEN)? If yes → CATASTROPHIC VIOLATION. Must be structurally impossible.
(4) Does any query, view, or export combine events from multiple session_ids into a single logical session? If yes → SEVERE VIOLATION of DOCTRINE-025.
(5) Does CONTINUED_PRESENCE reopen the prior session instead of creating a new one? If yes → FIX. (DOCTRINE-026)
(6) Is the FORCE_CLOSE vs REJECT decision made at runtime by a user? If yes → FIX. It must be a facility-level admin configuration. (DOCTRINE-027)
(7) Does any hardcoded value of 48 hours exist in the codebase (not as a default, but as a fixed constant)? If yes → FIX. Must be configurable per facility within [60, 4320] minutes.
(8) Does the evidence packet SESSION_TIMEOUT event include the mandatory disclaimer language? If no → FIX. (DOCTRINE-024)
(9) Can a driver’s receipt from a FORCED_CLOSE scenario hide from them the fact that their prior session was force-closed? If yes → FIX. Disclosure is mandatory.
(10) Is pg_cron configured to run session-timeout-tick every 1 minute? If no → FIX. The timeout enforcement depends on this.


